body:
Test case - a macro that attempts to recursively set each pattern to 5.  I suppose this could be done more easily by using `$(...)*` on the right side, but my real use case has the recursive call inside a match expression.

```
#[feature(macro_rules)];

macro_rules! set_to_5 (
    (($fst:pat), $action:stmt) => (
        {
            let $fst = 5;
            $action
        }
    );
    (($fst:pat, $($rest:pat),*), $action:stmt) => (
        {
            let $fst = 5;
            set_to_5!(($($rest),*), $action)
        }
    )
)

fn main() {
    let mut x = 4;
    set_to_5!((a, b), {
        x = b; // this is OK
        x = a; // this fails
    });
}
```

rustc output:

```
huh.rs:22:12: 22:13 error: unresolved name `a`.
huh.rs:22         x = a;
                      ^
huh.rs:3:0: 16:1 note: in expansion of set_to_5!
huh.rs:13:12: 14:9 note: expansion site
huh.rs:3:0: 16:1 note: in expansion of set_to_5!
huh.rs:20:4: 23:7 note: expansion site
error: aborting due to previous error
task 'rustc' failed at 'explicit failure', /usr/src/rust/src/libsyntax/diagnostic.rs:101
task '<main>' failed at 'explicit failure', /usr/src/rust/src/librustc/lib.rs:396
```

But if I substitute the --pretty expanded output, it compiles fine:

```
fn main() { let mut x = 4; { let a = 5; { let b = 5; { x = b; x = a; } } }; }
```

I'm new to Rust, so I don't know if this is intentional fallout from macro hygiene, but I don't see why the inner definition would work but not the outer one.
